[normal]1.1.
[normal] 
[normal]This is a submission to the Commons Select Committee enquiry on passenger transport in isolated communities on behalf of Norfolk Community Transport Association (NCTA).  NCTA is a membership organisation of individual community transport operators in 
[normal]Norfo
[normal]lk
[normal].  We currently have 33 members out of an estimated 70 provider organisations in the county
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2.
[normal] 
[normal]The points addressed by this submission are in relation to two specific questions posed by the select committee:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3.
[normal] 
[normal]The points within 
[normal]this submission are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4.[bold] 
[normal]We recognise that Norfolk County Council has also submitted evidence in [bold]response to this call and that the current demand for transport in the county[bold] and the profile of residents most in need of transport[bold] will have been outlined in that submission.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]ommunity 
[normal]T
[normal]ransport 
[normal]O
[normal]perator
[normal]s
[normal] (CTOs)
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2.
[normal] 
[normal]Fifteen operators are running one or more minibuses.  The largest operator has a fleet of over 60 buses and the smallest have one 
[normal]or two buses, which primarily offer transport to the activities run by the member organisation.  Seven operators run transport provision only.
[normal]  These organisations operate on Section 19 or Section 22 licences and include paid and volunteer drivers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3.
[normal] 
[normal]Fifty-
[normal]eight operators run community car schemes only  These are delivered by volunteer drivers using their own cars and are supported by voluntary co-ordinators (in about three organisations there is a paid, part time co-ordinator) and voluntary management commi
[normal]ttees/trustees.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4.
[normal] 
[normal]Other members are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5.
[normal] 
[normal]Norfolk County Council currently provides £283,350 in grants to 
[normal]some of 
[normal]these operators and has additionally 
[normal]been 
[normal]awarded contracts to provide specific services such as operating
[normal] demand responsive transport, school transport 
[normal]etc
[normal].  Some district councils provide funding to 
[normal]operators to subsidise the cost of the journey for the individual passenger
[normal], for health purposes
[normal].  Some parish councils also offer a subsidy in their areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6.
[normal] 
[normal]Community Transport Operators are independent community based organisations that have been set up by groups of local people responding to community needs.  Some in 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] have been running for over 20 years.  Some are thriving with pools of up to 50 volun
[normal]teer drivers while some are struggling, unable to recruit new drivers and not seeking to offer a service to people other than existing, long-term users.  As a result, coverage within the county is inconsistent, in terms of where 
[normal]o
[normal]perators ar
[normal]e based and wha
[normal]t their offer is 
[normal](some CTO
[normal]s support volunteers with the offer of free transport in return for their volunteering role.  This assists those who 
[normal]have been long term unemployed
[normal] to evidence their commitment to developing skills and experience and 
[normal]can 
[normal]result in
[normal] them being offered paid employment).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.
[normal] 
[normal]Bus operators provide a range of services including traditional door-to-door, dial-a-ride services in accessible minibuses.  Passengers book a journey and are co
[normal]llected from their home, taken to their destination
[normal],
[normal] collected 
[normal]and taken home again at a pre-arranged time.  They pay a fare and drivers (or passenger assistants) help them on and off the 
[normal]bus, 
[normal]carry shopping and ensure they are secured in their seats befor
[normal]e departing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal] 
[normal]Bus operators also deliver services to Norfolk County Council and others, including a demand responsive transport service called ‘
[normal]Flexibus
[normal]’ in 
[normal]5
[normal] parts of Norfolk; school transport, particularly for those needing accessible vehicles, adult soc
[normal]ial care journeys, such as to day centres, etc.  These are contracts awarded in a competitive environment.
[normal]  Some CTs provide feeder services to other transport hubs, particularly from isolated rural communities  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.
[normal] 
[normal]Car Schemes are focused particularly on he
[normal]alth based journeys, including to doctors’ surgeries, hospital appointments, dentists, opticians, chiropodists, etc.  So
[normal]me also take people shopping or 
[normal]to community based 
[normal]and well-being 
[normal]activities.  They are based in a specific geographic area
[normal]s
[normal] and offer s
[normal]ervices only to people living in a particular parish, village or market town.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.
[normal] 
[normal]Most of the passengers 
[normal]using community transport 
[normal]are older people, people with a disability or a health problem.  Many are 
[normal]much older people aged 80+ and a significant proport
[normal]ion 
[normal](70 – 80%) 
[normal]are women.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.
[normal] 
[normal]The key factors influencing the environment in which community transport is operating in 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An aging population – as well as national demographics, 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] is a popular retirement area.  Most rural districts have 
[normal]p
[normal]opulations of people aged over 75 that are significantly higher than the national average (fig 1)
[normal]. The figure for 
[normal]North Norfolk
[normal] is particularly high.
