[normal]4.1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The age of users of a sample group of CTOs in a survey commissioned by Norfolk County Council in 2012 can be seen in fig 2.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fig 2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Decreasing access to funded hospital transport – although it is claimed that the eligibility criteria have not changed, there is extensive reported evidence that criteria are being applied
[normal] more narrowly,
[normal] to limit access to this service.  The result is a si
[normal]gnificant increase in demand for community transport.  One of our members, North Norfolk Community Transport, reports 
[normal]just under 
[normal]a 
[normal]200
[normal]% increase in demand for its 
[normal]Medi
[normal]ride
[normal] service in the 
[normal]past two
[normal] year
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Decreasing public funding for investment in voluntar
[normal]y organisations at a time of recession, means that they are having to do more with less.  Norfolk County Council is maintaining its grant 
[normal]fund for co
[normal]mmunity transport in the next
[normal] financial year but is able to make no guarantees for the position 
[normal]beyond Marc
[normal]h 2015
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increasing requirements by funders for operators to meet requirements such as all drivers having Disclosure and Barring Service checks.  Although NCTA offers our members free checks for volunteer drivers, this is still an additional effort for vol
[normal]unteers to go through the checks and to co-ordinate the process.  Whilst these checks are undoubtedly necessary, they are time consuming and some volunteers are reluctant to go through the process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2.
[normal] 
[normal]NCTA undertook a piece of research in autumn 2012 
[normal]in 17 i
[normal]dentified parishes
[normal] in the centre of the county to support a funding bid we were making for a new demand responsive transport service in that area
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]We circulated links to an on line survey and additionally distributed 464 hard copies and others were circul
[normal]ated by Parish Clerks.  We received 109 returns.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.
[normal] 
[normal]The headline findings 
[normal]we
[normal]re:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4.
[normal] 
[normal]The most important aspects 
[normal]of the service were the hours of
[normal] operation (82%), availability at weekends (64%) and booking at short notice (45%).  40% of respondents said that home 
[normal]pick ups
[normal] were important to them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5.
[normal] 
[normal]People made comments about how ba
[normal]dly a bus service was needed in the area, how they felt isolated and that journeys were long and difficult and also expensive.  Respondents with disabilities and those with caring responsibilities for others were particularly supportive of the prospective 
[normal]service.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6.
[normal] 
[normal]The biggest demand for transport expressed in NCC’s survey was in the areas of accessing essential services and socialising and meeting family and friends.  These were seen 
[normal]a
[normal]s important indicators in people’s well being.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal] 
[normal]There are a number of factors that limit community transport from playing a wider role in delivering transport services.  The limitations do not include enthusiasm and a willingness to deliver.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal] 
[normal]There is a limit to what volunteers ca
[normal]n be expected to do.  Most volunteers do not want to work early in the morning, late in the evening or at weekends.  This limits the services that can be offered by volunteer dependent operators.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal] 
[normal]CTOs
[normal] tend to work in very specific areas and if there is no
[normal] scheme in a particular community, it cannot be imposed from a top down position.  This can result in areas of need not having access to a CT scheme while more affluent communities, with more access to volunteers with nice cars, have thriving schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.
[normal] 
[normal]Man
[normal]y potential passengers cannot afford longer journeys in a CT vehicle, even though they are cheaper than commercial alternatives.  Many people in 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] live 20 miles or more from a major hospital, which would result in a round trip costing around £18.  Ou
[normal]t of county trips to specialist hospitals such as 
[normal]Papworth
[normal] could cost around £90 (this might be reduced if a subsidy is available but the passenger would still have to pay £45).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.
[normal] 
[normal]Only CTOs running buses with Section 22 licences are eligible to accept 
[normal]concessionary travel passes.  This limits their ability to offer affordable transport to some of the most disadvantaged groups of people in the community and means that some operators have extra
[normal] administration from running two
[normal] different types of licence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.6.
[normal] 
[normal]CTOs experienced a significant drop in demand for services purchased by adult social services department as a result in cuts to local government funding affecting day centres.  Many of these have closed with the result that some 
[normal]isolated individuals have n
[normal]owhere to go and no opportunity to use the transport that is available to them.  CTOs had a sudden drop in income that has affected their ability to run sustainable services.
[normal]  
[normal]The introduction of personalised budgets has also had an impact on CTOs as previ
[normal]ous contracts to provide transport for groups of people from Social Services departments have ended and there is no automatic inclusion of transport costs when individuals plan and agree their budgets.  Some people are making the decision to buy their tran
[normal]sport from a range of sources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.
[normal] 
[normal]There are a number of barriers faced by Community Transport Operators in 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal].  The main ones are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The commissioning agenda – CTOs are seeking full cost recovery from 
[normal]contracts so that other areas of income are not cross-subsidising local authority contracts.  They are competing against commercial providers who are putting in very low bids that are acting as a loss leader.  Sometimes this results in these organisations 
[normal]having to withdraw from contracts before completion.  Norfolk County Council is seeking to cut their costs and
[normal] many standard contracts are awarded
[normal] only on the basis of price rather than value for money.  The Public Services (Social Value) Act is having lim
[normal]ited impact in changing this culture although a recent transport contract did include social criteria.  CTOs will not bid for contracts if they don’t make 
[normal]an operating surplus
[normal] from them
[normal].  
[normal]The majority of c
[normal]ontracts issued by NCC tend to be short term (1 yea
[normal]r) that do not enable contract holders to develop long term plans
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of engagement by health providers in CT.  GP surgeries and hospitals 
[normal]a
[normal]r
[normal]e the main organisational beneficiaries of community transport but make no financial contribution to the services
[normal].  CTOs could help to reduce costs of non emergency medical transport to the ambulance service, freeing resources to concentrate on emergency services.
[normal]  This would also achieve other cost savings for health providers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recruiting volunteers – this is a con
[normal]stant concern for all types of CTO.  As described above, the volunteer profile is aging and 
[normal]some schemes are not able to recruit younger volunteers.
[normal]  
[normal]There is a lack of trustee volunteers coming forward to take over from aging ones 
[normal]on
[normal] CT
[normal]O
[normal] 
[normal]boards
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]travel expenses
[normal] rate for volunteers is set at 45p for 
[normal]up to
[normal]10,000 miles
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] B
[normal]eyond this, the volunteer is deemed to be in profit and is not insured. This limits the amount a volunteer car driver can
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]do
[normal],
[normal] particularly with the increase in the longer runs for h
[normal]ospital car journeys.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An aging fleet of vehicles – a recent audit undertaken by NCTA identified that 70% of the bus fleet is between 5 – 10 years old and 27% is over 10 years old
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Changes to D1 status of driving licences – this is a problem that is beginn
[normal]ing to occur as drivers who passed their tests after 
[normal]1996
[normal] n
[normal]eed to take an additional test to be eligible to drive a minibus.  This costs over £1000 per driver and poses a significant extra cost for CTOs.  It also reinforces the dependency on older drivers 
[normal]who have D1 status on their licences
[normal].  
[normal]CTO
[normal]s could attract younger drivers, pay for them to take the additional test to drive minibuses, only to lose them to commercial operators.  The CTO would then have to begin the recruitment process from scratch
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Req
[normal]uired training for each driver includes:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Additional costs of providing accessible services, such as t
[normal]he 
[normal]price
[normal] of fully accessible vehicles compared to standard minibuses – a new
[normal],
[normal] standard vehicle can cost in the region of £18 – 20,000 
[normal]compared to £
[normal]38 – 40,000 for a fully accessible minibus.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Commercial operators tend to carry a maximum of one designated 
[normal]wheelchair on any journey.  This is reflecte
[normal]d in their fare structure.  
[normal]S
[normal]ome CTOs carry multiple large customised wheelchairs, scooters and mobility aids.  This restricts the amount of fare paying passengers.  A 16 
[normal]seater
[normal] fully accessible minibus can only 
[normal]accommodate seven passengers due to the 
[normal]number
[normal] of wheelchair mobility aids.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he time it takes the majority of passengers to get from their door onto the bus, to find their seat and put their seat belt on.  For individuals who travel in their wheelchair
[normal]s,
[normal] 
[normal]additional time is required to apply all the safety restraints (6) for each wheelchair.  Those passengers who need a wheelchair or scooter to get from their house to the bus and 
[normal]from the bus, 
[normal]once they have arrived 
[normal]at their destination
[normal],
[normal] take considerably l
[normal]onger and therefore each journey is less time efficient than a similar journey undertaken by a commercial operator
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An additional cost for CTOs is for safety equipment suc
[normal]h as wheelchair restraints (front and back), wheel chair occupant safety seat belt re
[normal]straints, seat belt extensions.  The cost is on average £600 per wheelchair.  Some CTOs have up to £3,000 of additional safety equipment on each bus.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2.
[normal] 
[normal]In general, CTOs face the same issues as many other third sector organisations including an increasingly 
[normal]competitive bidding process to win grant funding and the processes taking an increasing amount of time with more and more complexity in completing each application.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.
[normal] 
[normal]In order to overcome these barriers, the following actions could be taken:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increase skills within CTOs to bid for and win contracts
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Public authorities take social value into account when issuing contracts, publish full details about when current 
[normal]contracts are due for renewal and bidding processes are advertised in good time.  Contracts are awarded on the basis of value for money over the lifetime of the contract rather than the lowest price
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Contracts should be offered for 
[normal]longer periods, ideally 
[normal]a 
[normal]minimum 
[normal]five year term
[normal] (with an option to extend a further 3 years)
[normal],
[normal] which will 
[normal]enable CTOs to plan over longer periods and become more sustainable businesses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Local support 
[normal]should
[normal] 
[normal]be 
[normal]available to assist in the recruitment of volunteers
[normal] specifically for
[normal] driving
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Investment funds are available to enable CTOs to buy new vehicles (Norfolk County Council is currently offering a Small Vehicles Fund of £250
[normal],000 but this is a one off oppo
[normal]rtunity
[normal]).  This should be conditional upon CTOs operating a depreciation p
[normal]olicy with a vehicle replacement fund in their budgets.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government sh
[normal]ould review the D1 status on driving licenses or set up a ring fenced fund for CTOs to access funds for training drivers to drive minibuses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government should review the LTA Section
[normal]19 s
[normal]ervice so that all CTOs are eligible to accept concessionary bus passes  without having to apply for and run a section 22 route.
[normal]7.1.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The growing movement towards setting up local community transport forums should be recognised as highly beneficial to the secto
[normal]r and supported to develop and grow.  The benefits of this kind of support are identified below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.1.
[normal] 
[normal]NCTA is a local support organisation that enables CT
[normal]Os
[normal] in 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] to get together and develop th
[normal]eir organisations offering more and better services to local residents.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.2.
[normal] 
[normal]The specific services we offer are outlined below:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3.
[normal] 
[normal]Pooling resources to save money
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We offer a shared minibus insurance scheme, saving most operators approximately £100 per vehicle
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We produce shared publicity materials
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We run an HR contract with a specialist provider so that members can access support with staffing matters
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Working with Suffolk Community Transport we produced a Drivers Handbook for each driver to have in their vehic
[normal]le.  13 of our members took up this offer
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.
[normal] 
[normal]Improving performance and capacity
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Over 300 drivers having access to best practice policies and procedures in the drivers handbook
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Developing a learning programme to enable CTOs to become more sustainable, inclu
[normal]ding bidding for contracts
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Facilitating members getting together to share skills and ideas
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Commissioning a health and safety audit of member organisations
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Commissioning a vehicle audit for bus operators
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5.
[normal] 
[normal]Raising awareness of CT
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Attending events
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Raising awareness within health provider organisations
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Producing publicity materials and distributing them across the county
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Managing a website and database of all CT providers in the county and ensuring this is kept up to date so that other organisation
[normal]s have access to this information 
